he country.\r\n\r\n<strong><a name="footnote_1">[1]</a></strong> Many who subscribe to the idea of neurodiversity follow Jim Sinclair and use either “autists” or “autistics” to denote those with autism. Rejecting “people first” language, which implies that autism is both secondary and regrettable, autists understand their condition as an essential part of who they are, bringing with it both challenges and gifts.', 'On to College!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '911-revision-7', '', '', '2012-05-06 14:01:06', '2012-05-06 21:01:06', '', 911, 'http://www.ralphsavarese.com/uncategorized/911-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
